ut simultaneous modular congruences</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>Chinese remainder theorem</b> states that if=
 one knows the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division"=
 title=3D"Euclidean division">remainders of the Euclidean division</a> of a=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integ=
er</a> <i>n</i> by several integers, then one can determine uniquely the re=
mainder of the division of <i>n</i> by the product of these integers, under=
 the condition that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor" t=
itle=3D"Divisor">divisors</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Pairwise_coprime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pairwise coprime">pairwise=
 coprime</a> (no two divisors share a common factor other than 1).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sun_Tzu_Chinese_remainder_theorem.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/9/9d/Sun_Tzu_Chinese_remainder_theorem.svg/250px-Sun_Tzu_Chi=
nese_remainder_theorem.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"=
375" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"=
768"></a><figcaption>Sunzi's original formulation: <span class=3D"nowrap"><=
i>x</i> =E2=89=A1 2 (mod 3)</span> <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=89=A1 3 (mod =
5)</span> <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=89=A1 2 (mod 7)</span> <span class=3D"=
nowrap">with the solution</span> <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>x</i> =3D 23&nbs=
p;+=E2=80=89105<i>k</i>,</span> <span class=3D"nowrap">with <i>k</i> an int=
eger</span></figcaption></figure>
<p>The theorem is sometimes called <b>Sunzi's theorem</b>. Both names of th=
e theorem refer to its earliest known statement that appeared in <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunzi_Suanjing" title=3D"Sunzi Suanjing">=
Sunzi Suanjing</a></i>, a Chinese manuscript written during the 3rd to 5th =
century CE. This first statement was restricted to the following example:
</p><p>If one knows that the remainder of <i>n</i> divided by 3 is 2, the r=
emainder of <i>n</i> divided by 5 is 3, and the remainder of <i>n</i> divid=
ed by 7 is 2, then with no other information, one can determine the remaind=
er of <i>n</i> divided by 105 (the product of 3, 5, and 7) without knowing =
the value of <i>n</i>. In this example, the remainder is 23. Moreover, this=
 remainder is the only possible positive value of <i>n</i> that is less tha=
n 105.
</p><p>The Chinese remainder theorem is widely used for computing with larg=
e integers, as it allows replacing a computation for which one knows a boun=
d on the size of the result by several similar computations on small intege=
rs.
</p><p>The Chinese remainder theorem (expressed in terms of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic#Congruence" title=3D"Modular a=
rithmetic">congruences</a>) is true over every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal_domain" title=3D"Principal ideal domain">princ=
ipal ideal domain</a>. It has been generalized to any <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (mathematics)">ring</=
a>, with a formulation involving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
wo-sided_ideal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Two-sided ideal">two-sided i=
deals</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChinese_remainder_theo=
rem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>The earliest known statement of the problem appears in the 5th-century b=
ook <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunzi_Suanjing" title=3D"Su=
nzi Suanjing">Sunzi Suanjing</a></i> by the Chinese mathematician Sunzi:<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Katz_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-Katz-2"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>There are certain things whose numbe=
r is unknown. If we count them by threes, we have two left over; by fives, =
we have three left over; and by sevens, two are left over. How many things =
are there?<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></b=
lockquote>
<p>Sunzi's work would not be considered a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theorem">theorem</a> by modern standards; it only=
 gives one particular problem, without showing how to solve it, much less a=
ny <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title=3D"Ma=
thematical proof">proof</a> about the general case or a general <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> =
for solving it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
An algorithm for solving this problem was described by <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabhata" title=3D"Aryabhata">Aryabhata</a> (6th cent=
ury).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Special cas=
es of the Chinese remainder theorem were also known to <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brahmagupta" title=3D"Brahmagupta">Brahmagupta</a> (7t=
h century) and appear in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci=
" title=3D"Fibonacci">Fibonacci</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Liber_Abaci" title=3D"Liber Abaci">Liber Abaci</a> (1202).<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chin=
ese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The result was later generali=
zed with a complete solution called <i>Da-yan-shu</i> (<span title=3D"Chine=
se-language text"><span lang=3D"zh">=E5=A4=A7=E8=A1=8D=E8=A1=93</span></spa=
n>) in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qin_Jiushao" title=3D"Qin J=
iushao">Qin Jiushao</a>'s 1247 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mathematical_Treatise_in_Nine_Sections" title=3D"Mathematical Treatise in N=
ine Sections">Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections</a></i> <sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chine=
se_remainder_theorem#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which was translated into Engl=
ish in early 19th century by British missionary <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Alexander_Wylie_(missionary)" title=3D"Alexander Wylie (missi=
onary)">Alexander Wylie</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-8"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
