<p>The notion of congruences was first introduced and used by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich G=
auss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Disquisitiones_Arithmeticae" title=3D"Disquisitiones Arithmeticae">D=
isquisitiones Arithmeticae</a></i> of 1801.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theo=
rem#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Gauss illustrates the Chinese remainder theor=
em on a problem involving calendars, namely, "to find the years that have a=
 certain period number with respect to the solar and lunar cycle and the Ro=
man indiction."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-11"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Gauss introduces a procedure for solving the problem that had already bee=
n used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D=
"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> but was in fact an ancient method that =
had appeared several times.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#cite_note-12=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
