n></div>
<p>Let <i>n</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>n</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> be integers g=
reater than 1, which are often called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">moduli</a></i> or <=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euc=
lidean division">divisors</a></i>. Let us denote by <i>N</i> the product of=
 the <i>n</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>.
</p><p>The Chinese remainder theorem asserts that if the <i>n</i><sub><i>i<=
/i></sub> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pairwise_coprime" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pairwise coprime">pairwise coprime</a>, and if=
 <i>a</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>a</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> are integers such t=
hat 0 =E2=89=A4 <i>a</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> &lt; <i>n</i><sub><i>i</i></sub=
> for every <i>i</i>, then there is one and only one integer <i>x</i>, such=
 that 0 =E2=89=A4 <i>x</i> &lt; <i>N</i> and the remainder of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euclidean di=
vision">Euclidean division</a> of <i>x</i> by <i>n</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> i=
s <i>a</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> for every <i>i</i>.
</p><p>This may be restated as follows in terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
