<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Systematic_search">Systemat=
ic search</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCh=
inese_remainder_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Systematic search"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is easy to check whether a value of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> is a solution: it suffices to compute the=
 remainder of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_divisi=
on" title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean division</a> of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> by each <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>n</i><sub><i>i</i></sub></span>. Thus, to find the solution, it =
suffices to check successively the integers from <span class=3D"texhtml">0<=
/span> to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span=
> until finding the solution.
</p><p>Although very simple, this method is very inefficient. For the simpl=
e example considered here, <span class=3D"texhtml">40</span> integers (incl=
uding <span class=3D"texhtml">0</span>) have to be checked for finding the =
solution, which is <span class=3D"texhtml">39</span>. This is an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Exponential time">exponential time</a> algorithm, as the size of the i=
nput is, up to a constant factor, the number of digits of <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span>, and the average number o=
f operations is of the order of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">N</span>.
</p><p>Therefore, this method is rarely used, neither for hand-written comp=
utation nor on computers.
</p>
