<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Over_principal_ideal_domain=
s">Over principal ideal domains</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DChinese_remainder_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Over principal ideal domains"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem#St=
atement">=C2=A7&nbsp;Statement</a>, the Chinese remainder theorem has been =
stated in three different ways: in terms of remainders, of congruences, and=
 of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_isomorphism" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Ring isomorphism">ring isomorphism</a>. The statement =
in terms of remainders does not apply, in general, to <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal_domain" title=3D"Principal ideal domain=
">principal ideal domains</a>, as remainders are not defined in such <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (mathe=
matics)">rings</a>. However, the two other versions make sense over a princ=
ipal ideal domain <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i></span>: it suffices to r=
